  "Core, mantle, crust, and ocean": "",
  "Atmosphere, hydrosphere, geosphere, and biosphere": "",
  "Troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, and thermosphere": "",
  "Earth system simulations model interactions among the four major spheres: the atmosphere (air), hydrosphere (water), geosphere (solid Earth), and biosphere (living organisms), along with energy flows between them.": "",
  "In Earth system simulations, what drives the global atmospheric circulation pattern?": "",
  "Earth's magnetic field, particularly regarding between as": "",
  "Volcanic emissions alone, particularly regarding deflects when": "",
  "Unequal solar heating between the equator and poles combined with Earth's rotation": "",
  "Tidal forces from the Moon under the given assumptions": "",
  "Global atmospheric circulation is driven primarily by the unequal distribution of solar energy between equatorial and polar regions, combined with the Coriolis effect from Earth's rotation, which deflects moving air masses.": "",
  "Which computational approach divides the Earth into a three-dimensional grid to solve equations governing fluid motion?": "",
  "Statistical regression": "",
  "General Circulation Model (GCM)": "",
  "Analog computing": "",
  "Simple box model": "",
  "General Circulation Models (GCMs) divide the atmosphere and ocean into a three-dimensional grid and solve the fundamental equations of fluid dynamics, thermodynamics, and radiative transfer at each grid point over successive time steps.": "",
  "What is the primary greenhouse gas responsible for the largest share of human-caused warming in Earth system simulations?": "",
  "Nitrous oxide": "",
  "Ozone": "",
  "Carbon dioxide": "",
  "Methane": "",
  "While multiple greenhouse gases contribute to warming, carbon dioxide (CO2) is responsible for the largest share of anthropogenic radiative forcing due to its abundance and long atmospheric residence time of centuries to millennia.": "",
  "How do Earth system models represent the carbon cycle?": "",
  "By tracking only fossil fuel emissions": "",
  "By tracking carbon fluxes between the atmosphere, ocean, land vegetation, and soils": "",
  "By ignoring biological processes": "",
  "By only measuring CO2 in the atmosphere": "",
  "Earth system models represent the carbon cycle by simulating carbon fluxes among multiple reservoirs including the atmosphere, ocean surface and deep water, terrestrial vegetation, soils, and sediments, as well as anthropogenic emissions.": "",
  "What phenomenon do Earth system simulations predict will intensify as global temperatures rise?": "",
  "A decrease in all forms of precipitation globally": "",
  "Complete cessation of ocean currents": "",
  "The water cycle, with more intense precipitation events and longer droughts": "",
  "Uniform temperature increases everywhere on Earth": "",
  "Earth system simulations consistently predict that the hydrological cycle will intensify with warming because warmer air holds more moisture. This leads to more intense precipitation events in wet regions and prolonged droughts in dry regions.": "",
  "What role does ocean thermohaline circulation play in Earth system simulations?": "",
  "It generates all of Earth's volcanic activity": "",
  "It only affects coastal tides": "",
  "It transports heat from the tropics toward the poles and distributes nutrients through the deep ocean": "",
  "It is irrelevant to global climate": "",
  "Thermohaline circulation, driven by differences in water density from temperature and salinity variations, acts as a global conveyor belt that transports heat poleward, distributes nutrients, and helps regulate global climate patterns over long timescales.": "",
  "Which Representative Concentration Pathway (RCP) scenario assumes the highest greenhouse gas emissions by 2100?": "",
  "RCP 4.5": "",
  "RCP 2.6": "",
  "RCP 8.5": "",
  "RCP 6.0": "",
  "RCP 8.5 represents the highest emission scenario with radiative forcing reaching 8.5 watts per square meter by 2100, corresponding to continued high fossil fuel use without significant mitigation efforts.": "",
  "What is the approximate climate sensitivity range (temperature increase for doubling of CO2) used in most Earth system models?": "",
  "0.1 to 0.5 degrees Celsius": "",
  "10 to 15 degrees Celsius": "",
  "Exactly 2.0 degrees Celsius in all models": "",
  "1.5 to 4.5 degrees Celsius": "",
  "The equilibrium climate sensitivity, defined as the long-term temperature change from doubling atmospheric CO2, is estimated to be in the range of 1.5 to 4.5 degrees Celsius based on multiple lines of evidence and model results from the IPCC.": "",
  "Why do Earth system models require supercomputers to run?": "",
  "Because they only work on expensive hardware": "",
  "Because solving millions of equations across a global 3D grid over thousands of time steps demands enormous computational power": "",
  "Because the models are poorly designed and inefficient": "",
  "Because they need to display high-resolution graphics": "",
  "Earth system models solve complex systems of differential equations at millions of grid points in three dimensions, stepping forward through time with small increments, which requires trillions of calculations and can only be completed in reasonable time using supercomputers.": "",
  "What is an Earth System Model (ESM)?": "",
  "A physical globe used in classrooms, particularly regarding couples in most standard conditions": "",
  "A simple calculator for weather statistics, particularly regarding that when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "A satellite that photographs the Earth, particularly regarding models under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "A comprehensive computer simulation that couples atmospheric, oceanic, land surface, ice, and biogeochemical components to represent the full Earth system": "",
  "An Earth System Model is a comprehensive computational framework that couples multiple component models representing the atmosphere, ocean, land surface, sea ice, and biogeochemical cycles to simulate the interactions among all major components of the Earth system.": "",
  "What does 'radiative forcing' mean in Earth system science?": "",
  "The total amount of sunlight reaching Earth's surface": "",
  "The force exerted by radiation pressure on satellites": "",
  "The change in net energy flux at the top of the atmosphere caused by an external driver such as greenhouse gases or solar variability": "",
  "The electromagnetic radiation emitted by radio towers": "",
  "Radiative forcing measures the change in the net energy balance at the tropopause caused by an external factor, expressed in watts per square meter. Positive forcing warms the system while negative forcing cools it.": "",
  "What is 'albedo' in Earth system simulations?": "",
  "The salinity of ocean water": "",
  "The fraction of incoming solar radiation reflected by a surface": "",
  "The temperature of the Earth's core": "",
  "The speed of tectonic plate movement": "",
  "Albedo is the fraction of incoming solar radiation that is reflected back to space by a surface. Ice and snow have high albedo (reflecting most sunlight), while dark ocean water and forests have low albedo (absorbing most sunlight).": "",
  "What does 'climate feedback' mean in the context of Earth system simulations?": "",
  "User comments about climate model performance": "",
  "The time delay between emission and warming": "",
  "A process that amplifies or dampens an initial climate perturbation": "",
  "The feedback survey sent to climate scientists": "",
  "A climate feedback is a process triggered by an initial climate change that either amplifies (positive feedback) or dampens (negative feedback) the original perturbation. The ice-albedo feedback and water vapor feedback are key examples in Earth system models.": "",
  "What is meant by 'coupled model' in Earth system simulations?": "",
  "A model that links two or more component models so they exchange information at each time step": "",
  "A model that runs on two computers simultaneously": "",
  "A model developed by exactly two research groups": "",
  "A model that only simulates two variables": "",
  "A coupled model connects two or more component models (such as atmosphere and ocean) so they exchange energy, mass, and momentum at regular intervals during the simulation, allowing feedbacks between the components to develop naturally.": "",
  "What does 'transient climate response' mean?": "",
  "The temperature change at the time of CO2 doubling in a simulation where CO2 increases gradually at 1% per year": "",
  "The immediate temperature change when a volcano erupts": "",
  "The time it takes for climate to return to normal after a perturbation": "",
  "The maximum temperature Earth can reach": "",
  "Transient climate response (TCR) is defined as the global mean temperature change at the time atmospheric CO2 has doubled in a simulation with CO2 increasing at 1% per year. It is typically lower than equilibrium climate sensitivity because the ocean has not fully warmed.": "",
  "What is 'grid resolution' in Earth system models?": "",
  "The size of the individual computational cells that divide the model domain": "",
  "The resolution of satellite images used as input": "",
  "The number of scientists who resolved to build the model": "",
  "The screen resolution of the display showing model output": "",
  "Grid resolution refers to the size of the computational cells into which the atmosphere, ocean, and land surface are divided. Typical modern climate models use grid cells of 50-100 km for the atmosphere and 10-50 km for the ocean.": "",
  "What does 'carbon sink' mean in Earth system science?": "",
  "A place where carbon is destroyed permanently": "",
  "A type of kitchen fixture made of carbon fiber": "",
  "An industrial facility that produces carbon dioxide": "",
  "A reservoir that absorbs more carbon from the atmosphere than it releases": "",
  "A carbon sink is any reservoir that absorbs and stores more carbon than it releases over a given time period. The ocean and terrestrial vegetation are major carbon sinks, currently absorbing roughly half of human CO2 emissions.": "",
  "What is meant by 'tipping point' in Earth system simulations?": "",
  "The moment when two models produce identical results": "",
  "The point at which funding for climate research ends": "",
  "A threshold beyond which a system undergoes a rapid, potentially irreversible shift to a new state": "",
  "The exact moment a model starts running": "",
  "A tipping point is a critical threshold in the Earth system where a small additional perturbation can trigger a large, often abrupt and potentially irreversible transition to a qualitatively different state, such as the collapse of ice sheets or dieback of major forests.": "",
  "What does 'aerosol forcing' mean in climate simulations?": "",
  "The force applied by aerosol spray cans when evaluated systematically": "",
  "The radiative effect of tiny suspended particles in the atmosphere that can scatter or absorb sunlight and modify cloud properties": "",
  "Air pressure changes caused by wind turbines under normal circumstances": "",
  "The weight of dust particles on the ground when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Aerosol forcing refers to the radiative impact of atmospheric aerosol particles, which can directly scatter and absorb solar radiation (direct effect) and modify cloud formation and properties (indirect effect), generally producing a net cooling that partially offsets greenhouse warming.": "",
  "A student runs a simplified Earth system simulation and doubles the atmospheric CO2 concentration. The model shows an initial warming of 1.2 degrees Celsius from the direct greenhouse effect, but the final equilibrium warming is 3.0 degrees Celsius. What explains the additional 1.8 degrees of warming?": "",
  "A calculation error in the simulation": "",
  "Solar output increased simultaneously in the simulation": "",
  "The model doubled CO2 more than once": "",
  "Positive feedback mechanisms such as water vapor feedback and ice-albedo feedback amplified the initial warming": "",
  "The additional warming beyond the direct CO2 greenhouse effect comes from positive feedbacks. Warmer air holds more water vapor (itself a greenhouse gas), and melting ice reduces albedo, both amplifying the initial warming by a factor of approximately 2.5.": "",
  "An Earth system simulation shows that the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC) weakens by 30% over the next century under a high-emission scenario. A European policy maker asks what this means for Western Europe. What is the most accurate response based on current scientific understanding?": "",
  "Europe will experience an ice age, particularly regarding overturning in most standard conditions": "",
  "AMOC weakening could reduce the warming rate in parts of Western Europe relative to global averages, but overall warming from greenhouse gases would still dominate": "",
  "Western Europe will become a tropical climate, particularly regarding means when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "AMOC changes have no effect on European climate, particularly regarding western within the typical range of values": "",
  "A weakening AMOC would reduce northward heat transport to Western Europe, partially offsetting greenhouse warming in that region. However, most simulations show that greenhouse warming dominates, so Europe would still warm overall, just less than it would without the AMOC weakening.": "",
  "A group of AP students analyzes output from two Earth system models. Model X projects Arctic sea ice will disappear in summer by 2050, while Model Y projects this will not happen until 2080. Both models use the same emission scenario. What is the most likely explanation for this difference?": "",
  "The emission scenario was applied incorrectly to one model": "",
  "One of the models must be completely wrong": "",
  "Arctic sea ice is impossible to model": "",
  "The models differ in their representation of sea ice dynamics, ocean heat transport, and cloud feedbacks in the Arctic": "",
  "Different models use different parameterizations for sea ice physics, ocean heat transport, and cloud feedbacks, all of which strongly influence Arctic warming rates. This structural uncertainty between models is a major source of spread in projections for polar regions.": "",
  "In a classroom simulation, students model the carbon cycle by representing the atmosphere, ocean, and terrestrial biosphere as boxes with fluxes between them. They find that increasing the ocean temperature reduces CO2 absorption by the ocean. What fundamental principle explains this result?": "",
  "Temperature has no effect on gas solubility": "",
  "Warmer water evaporates all the CO2": "",
  "Warmer water holds less dissolved gas than cold water, reducing ocean CO2 uptake": "",
  "CO2 is only absorbed by ice, not liquid water": "",
  "The solubility of gases in water decreases as temperature increases. This means that as ocean temperatures rise, the ocean's capacity to absorb CO2 from the atmosphere diminishes, creating a positive feedback that leaves more CO2 in the atmosphere and increases warming.": "",
  "An AP exam question presents a graph showing that Earth system models consistently underestimate the rate of observed Arctic sea ice loss from 2000-2020. A student is asked to evaluate this discrepancy. Which response demonstrates the deepest understanding?": "",
  "The discrepancy suggests that models may not fully capture all positive feedbacks in the Arctic, such as ice-albedo feedback amplification, ocean heat transport changes, and black carbon deposition on ice": "",
  "Arctic ice loss is not related to climate change, particularly regarding showing when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The observations must be wrong since the models are always correct as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "The models are useless if they underestimate Arctic ice loss, particularly regarding earth as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "The most sophisticated analysis recognizes that model-observation discrepancies indicate areas where models need improvement. The underestimate of Arctic ice loss likely reflects missing or underrepresented feedbacks, motivating ongoing model development to better capture these complex processes.": "",
  "A researcher runs an Earth system simulation to study the effect of large-scale deforestation in the Amazon. The model predicts not only local temperature and precipitation changes but also shifts in rainfall patterns over distant regions. What concept does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Teleconnections, where changes in one region affect climate in distant areas through atmospheric and oceanic pathways": "",
  "Local changes can only affect local climate": "",
  "The model has an error because distant effects are impossible": "",
  "Deforestation only affects soil quality, not climate": "",
  "Teleconnections are climate linkages between geographically distant regions. Amazon deforestation reduces evapotranspiration and alters atmospheric circulation patterns, potentially affecting rainfall in regions thousands of kilometers away through changes in moisture transport and large-scale atmospheric waves.": "",
  "An AP student analyzes Earth system model output and notices that the model shows a 'committed warming' of 0.5 degrees Celsius even if all emissions stopped today. What causes this committed warming?": "",
  "The ocean has absorbed heat that will continue to warm the atmosphere as the climate system reaches equilibrium with current greenhouse gas levels": "",
  "The Sun is getting brighter": "",
  "The model continues to add emissions even after they are stopped": "",
  "Committed warming is a model artifact with no physical basis": "",
  "Committed warming occurs because the climate system has not yet fully responded to the greenhouse gases already in the atmosphere. The ocean's large thermal inertia means it has absorbed heat that will gradually be released, warming the surface further until a new equilibrium is reached.": "",
  "During an AP lab, students compare Earth system simulation output for pre-industrial conditions versus present day. They notice that simulated global temperatures in the pre-industrial control run are stable within plus or minus 0.2 degrees Celsius over 500 years, while the historical simulation shows a clear warming trend after 1950. What does the stable pre-industrial control demonstrate?": "",
  "That the model's internal variability alone is small, so the post-1950 warming trend in the historical simulation must be driven by external forcings like greenhouse gas increases": "",
  "Pre-industrial temperatures never varied at all, particularly regarding only under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The historical simulation is unreliable, particularly regarding produces in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The model cannot simulate any temperature changes, particularly regarding demonstrates as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The stable pre-industrial control run demonstrates that the model's natural internal variability produces only small temperature fluctuations. This makes the post-1950 warming in the historical simulation attributable to external forcings, primarily increasing greenhouse gas concentrations.": "",
  "A climate research team runs their Earth system model with and without volcanic aerosol forcing to study the 1991 Mount Pinatubo eruption. The simulation with volcanic forcing shows a temporary global cooling of about 0.5 degrees Celsius over 1-2 years, matching observations. What does this successful simulation demonstrate about the model?": "",
